628
69:21.630 --> 69:29.130
and specifically, it's
uniform over those strings that have binary dot
product equal to 0 with s.

629
69:29.130 --> 69:36.540
Now that we know how the circuit
for Simon's algorithm works and specifically what
the probabilities are for the different measurement outcomes,

630
69:36.540 --> 69:41.820
it remains to explain how this helps us to solve Simon's problem.

631
69:41.820 --> 69:49.290
Summarizing what we just learned, if it's the case that the function f satisfies the promise in Simon's problem,

632
69:49.290 --> 69:55.560
when the hidden string s
is the all-zero string, we obtain a completely random
string from the measurements,

633
69:55.560 --> 69:59.190
where each end bit string
y is equally likely.

634
69:59.190 --> 70:06.600
If on the other hand, the function f satisfies the promise for a different string s, one that's not equal
to the all-zero string,

635
70:06.600 --> 70:16.620
then we get a random string y having binary dot product
equal to 0 with s, and among all of those strings,
each y is equally likely.

636
70:16.620 --> 70:23.220
But we'll never get a string y having binary dot product
equal to 1 with s.

637
70:23.220 --> 70:31.560
The question becomes, "Is this enough information
to determine s?" And the answer, as I've
already suggested, is yes,

638
70:31.560 --> 70:36.450
provided that we run the
circuit enough times.

639
70:36.450 --> 70:43.020
Specifically, let's suppose
that we run the circuit k times, where K is equal to n plus r,

640
70:43.020 --> 70:48.330
where r is some number that's going to control the
likelihood that we recover s.

641
70:48.330 --> 70:56.160
Just as an example, if
we choose r to be 10, we'll be successful with
probability greater than 99.9%,

642
70:56.160 --> 71:00.000
so we don't need r to be all that large.

643
71:00.000 --> 71:09.060
In general, the probability of failure is less than the probability
of flipping a fair coin r times and getting heads every single time.

644
71:09.060 --> 71:16.950
So if 99.9% isn't good
enough, then take r to be 20, and the chance of failure is
less than one in a million,

645
71:16.950 --> 71:25.440
or choose whatever r
makes you comfortable. You can't guarantee a correct solution, but you can make the
probability of error negligible

646
71:25.440 --> 71:28.560
for all intents and purposes.

647
71:28.560 --> 71:35.580
Here we are naming these
strings y1 through yk, where we're using superscripts to help us to name these strings,

648
71:35.580 --> 71:40.290
just so that we can reserve subscripts to refer to the individual
bits of those strings.

649
71:40.290 --> 71:47.070
So these aren't exponents
or anything like that, these are just the names that we're giving to these k strings.

650
71:47.070 --> 71:54.390
Each one has length n because we got them
from running the circuit for Simon's algorithm.

651
71:54.390 --> 72:02.940
So we can write down the
individual bits of these k strings like you see right here.

652
72:02.940 --> 72:10.740
What we do now is to create a matrix m, where each entry of this matrix is a bit, and we get these bits from the strings

653
72:10.740 --> 72:14.880
that we just measured, just like as shown right here.

654
72:14.880 --> 72:22.620
So this matrix has k rows and n columns, and its entries are all binary values.

655
72:22.620 --> 72:30.300
Now, we don't know what s is. That's what we're trying to find, but just imagine for a
moment that we did know s,

656
72:30.300 --> 72:36.690
and we formed a column
vector from the bits of s, just like is shown right here.

657
72:36.690 --> 72:43.620
If we were to multiply that vector by m and then take the result modulo-2, or another way of saying that

658
72:43.620 --> 72:51.630
is that we replace addition
with the eXclusive OR, then we will necessarily
get the all-zero vector.

659
72:51.630 --> 72:57.660
That's because each of the
entries in this resulting vector is none other than the
binary dot product of s

660
72:57.660 --> 73:01.050
with one of the rows of m.

661
73:01.050 --> 73:06.960
If S happens to be the all-zero string, we'll always get the zero vector from the binary dot product.

662
73:06.960 --> 73:15.660
And if s is not the all-zero string, we'll get this from what we
know about the probabilities for the strings y1 through yk to appear.

663
73:15.660 --> 73:21.870
In particular, the
binary dot product with s is always zero for all of these strings.

664
73:21.870 --> 73:28.980
A simple way of saying that is that this vector
formed from the bits of s is always in the null
space of the matrix m,

665
73:28.980 --> 73:36.270
assuming that we're doing all
of our arithmetic modulo-2, but of course, we don't know what s is,

666
73:36.270 --> 73:39.630
we're trying to find s.

667
73:39.630 --> 73:46.800
But what we can do is that we can compute the
null space of this matrix m, once again, modulo-2.

668
73:46.800 --> 73:53.070
Specifically, we can do that using the technique of
Gaussian elimination, which is the procedure that's often taught

669
73:53.070 --> 73:56.430
in introductory linear algebra courses.

670
73:56.430 --> 74:04.830
It works perfectly well when we do all of our arithmetic modulo-2, and it can be done quite
efficiently with a computer.

671
74:04.830 --> 74:11.400
And if we compute the null space of m, given the specific way that these k strings have
been randomly chosen,

672
74:11.400 --> 74:18.180
we will be able to recover s with probability greater than
1 minus 2 to the negative r.

673
74:18.180 --> 74:26.310
To be specific, what we will see with probability greater than
1 minus 2 to the negative r is that the null space
includes the all-zero vector,

674
74:26.310 --> 74:34.200
as it always does for every matrix, as well as the vector corresponding to s, whether it's the all-zero vector or not.

675
74:34.200 --> 74:39.630
And most importantly, no other vectors will
appear in the null space.

676
74:39.630 --> 74:43.920
It's actually not too hard to prove this, although I won't go through it in detail.

